100TH STREET BRIDGE NEWS



Crews plan to close US-131 at 100th Street over the weekend to lay beams for the new bridge.

Northbound and southbound traffic will be directed off and back on over the exit/entrance ramps. During the closure, 100th Street traffic will not be able to get onto US-131, and US-131 traffic will not be able to access 100th Street.

The bridge replacement is expected to continue until October.

post_text:
MDOT announced that the 100th Street Bridge project will begin Monday, March 23: 100th Street will be closed to through-traffic between S. Kent Drive and Division Avenue with traffic detoured on Clyde Park Avenue, 84th Street, and Division Avenue. Traffic will be maintained on US-131 with traffic shifts and lane closures. Short-term closures for bridge demolition, beam setting, and paving will be in effect on US-131. Traffic will exit and re-enter the highway using the 100th Street off and on ramps. Alternating ramp closures will be in effect and traffic detoured to the adjacent interchanges at 142nd Avenue to the south and 84th Street to the north. The project is slated to be complete in October 2020.

Also, in the short term:

84th St between Division Ave and Eastern Ave will have intermittent lane closures for tree removal ‚Äì3-23-20 to 3-27-20
Division Ave between 84th St and 92nd St will have intermittent lane closures for guardrail replacement ‚Äì 3-17-20 to 3-27-20

The Byron Center Chamber of Commerce has come up with this event as a way for area businesses to promote themselves.
There is a friendly competition for Instagram also.
All the details can be read here:
http://www.byroncenterchamber.org/byron-rules-the-roost

The Idea of the Game
People will take pictures of themselves with the chickens and post them to Instagram using 2 hashtags:

#ByronRulesTheRoost (to identify the game)
#Chicken7 (to identify the chicken)

The chicken number is the number that is associated with the flyer and map that will be distributed, posted on our website, and is attached to this email.

We will be randomly selecting participants that have posted pictures to award them with gift certificates provided by Chamber Members.

Also, feel free to post your pictures to our facebook page and tag Byron Center Chamber of commerce.

post_id:
The Byron Center Chamber of Commerce has come up with this event as a way for area businesses to promote themselves.
There is a friendly competition for Instagram also.
All the details can be read here:
http://www.byroncenterchamber.org/byron-rules-the-roost

The Idea of the Game
People will take pictures of themselves with the chickens and post them to Instagram using 2 hashtags:

#ByronRulesTheRoost (to identify the game)
#Chicken7 (to identify the chicken)

The chicken number is the number that is associated with the flyer and map that will be distributed, posted on our website, and is attached to this email.

We will be randomly selecting participants that have posted pictures to award them with gift certificates provided by Chamber Members.

Also, feel free to post your pictures to our facebook page and tag Byron Center Chamber of commerce.

post_text:
Hello BCCS Families,

December is a busy time for student activities so I just wanted to send out a reminder for a few events that the student council is putting on. Candy Grams are currently being sold at lunch and in the office. They are sold for $1 each and will be delivered on 12/20.

The student council is also busy getting ready for the gingerbread house competition after school on 12/20. This event is free and open to students in grades 6-12. Please consider donating supplies for the kids to build and decorate their houses with! You can see the items needed in the sign up genius link below:

https://www.signupgenius.com/go/20f0d4aada823a6fa7-gingerbread1

If you have any questions please contact Jen Walenta at jwalenta@byroncentercharter.org.

Thank you and have a blessed holiday season,

Jen Walenta
High School Social Studies Teacher
Byron Center Charter School

Hello everyone,

Exciting news for some of our students participating in technology and design courses at KCTC! Tyce (a senior) is part of a group that has made it to the top round of the Samsung Solve for Tomorrow competition. They are one of 10 national winners earning them a HUGE prize of $150,000 worth of Samsung technology! Now, those 10 schools are competing for the public vote to win an extra prize of $20,000 in Samsung technology. Please help these kids win by voting at the link below! Currently they are in 4th place and need a boost to get them to first. You can vote once per day until April 2.

They are labeled as Kent Career Tech Center, MI
http://www.samsung.com/us/solvefortomorrow/

P.S. you should watch their 3 minute video, their idea is awesome!

Thank you for your help!
-Jen Walenta

Dear Parents and Guardians of BCCS Students,
BCCS will be closed again tomorrow ,Friday-2/9, due to widespread illness. At this time we have 44 or better than 17% of students out due to illness. The secondary is hardest hit: 24% of students absent, 4 out of 7 grade-levels having greater than 20% absent. and almost one half of 10 th grade students home ill. There have been a handful of students leave through mid-day today due to illness, and two teachers are out and will not be here tomorrow.
Despite our efforts to slow the frequency of absences due to illness, we are still experiencing a fair share of repeating and new absences due to illness. If we had the opportunity, I'd‚Ä¶ More
